Right now there is different way of batching updates in `react-dom` (`ReactDOM.unstable_batchedUpdates(() => { ... })` and eg. `react-native`.

Let's say I'm creating a library that can be used both on the web and in react-native. Let's say, I want to take advantage of using batched updates on both platforms.

However, implementing batched updates works differently on each platform.

On DOM it's `ReactDOM.unstable_batchedUpdates(() => { ... })`

On RN it's a bit hacky but seems to work. I've implemented it like

```tsx
function getBatchedUpdateFunction() {
  try {
    const renderer = __DEV__
      ? require('react-native/Libraries/Renderer/implementations/ReactNativeRenderer-dev')
      : require('react-native/Libraries/Renderer/implementations/ReactNativeRenderer-prod');

    if (!renderer) {
      return null;
    }

    if (!renderer.unstable_batchedUpdates) {
      return null;
    }

    return renderer.unstable_batchedUpdates;
  } catch (error) {
    return null;
  }
}

export function batchedUpdates(callback: () => void) {
  const batchedUpdatesFunction = getBatchedUpdateFunction();

  if (!batchedUpdatesFunction) {
    // we're not able to call batch function. Let's fallback to call callback normally without batching
    callback();
    return;
  }

  batchedUpdatesFunction(() => {
    callback();
  });
}
```

I also have to check in runtime, what platform is used to call proper batch function type

Is there any way to make it cleaner if I want to batch on any react-powered platform?

I assume there might be many 'env-agnostic', react based libs that use batching eg redux, mobx. Each of those should be usable on each react-based platform

