**What is the current behavior?**
React warns about key|ref not being a prop:
```
Warning: Child: `key` is not a prop. Trying to access it will result in `undefined` being returned. If you need to access the same value within the child component, you should pass it as a different prop. (https://fb.me/react-special-props)
```
However, when using `defaultProps` and _not_ providing a key|ref, the key|ref is used as a prop. Test:
```javascript
class Child extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return <div> {this.props.key} </div>;
  }
}
Child.defaultProps = {
  key: "example"
};
class Parent extends React.Component {
  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        <Child /> // <<<<< doesn't warn
        <Child key="1" /> // <<<<< warns
      </div>
    );
  }
}
```
This happens because: 
https://github.com/facebook/react/blob/3ad076472ce9108b9b8a6a6fe039244b74a34392/packages/react/src/ReactElement.js#L362-L384
assigning `defaultProps` doesn't take into account `RESERVED_PROPS`, so this condition `if (key || ref) {...` can be `false`

**What is the expected behavior?**
If `key|ref` is not a prop, it shouldn't map `defaultProps` reserved names to `props`

